<h2 id="legal-considerations">⚖️ Legal Considerations for 2026</h2>

Waiver enforceability continues evolving, and tour operators must stay current on requirements:

<strong>Electronic signature validity:</strong> The ESIGN Act and UETA provide federal foundation, but state-specific requirements vary. Smartwaiver's consent capture workflow is designed to meet the strictest state standards (including New Mexico's particularly demanding requirements).

<strong>Minor consent requirements:</strong> Several states have tightened guardian consent standards since 2024. Smartwaiver updated their minor participant workflow in early 2026 to address these changes.

<strong>Data privacy:</strong> CCPA and state-level privacy laws affect how waiver data can be stored and used. Smartwaiver's data handling meets current requirements, but operators should review their own data retention policies with legal counsel.

<strong>International guests:</strong> If you serve international visitors, waiver enforceability becomes more complex. GDPR implications for EU guests and similar regulations require careful attention to consent language and data handling.

We always recommend having an attorney licensed in your operating states review your specific waiver language, regardless of which platform you choose.

